timeline.bodyText: IIUC, the data is being sent from Source FhirStore to Destination FhirStore by the Fhir service itself, right? And we're just managing the Operation on the Dataflow side. Is that correct?
timeline.author: pabloem

replies.bodyText: Yep, exactly 👍 . We're just sending operation and wait for it to complete.
replies.author: trucleduc

timeline.bodyText: I think we should rename this to Export since GCS is an implementation detail here. Feel free to leave it to a follow-up PR.
timeline.author: lastomato
timeline.diffHunk:
@@ -122,12 +124,24 @@ * store) This requires each resource to contain a client provided ID. It is important that when * using import you give the appropriate permissions to the Google Cloud Healthcare Service Agent. * + *

ExportGcs This is to export FHIR resources from a FHIR store to Google Cloud Storage. The

replies.bodyText: Good point. The reason I want to keep this as ExportGcs is there is also an ExportBQ. I agree that both are implementation details, but depending on usage, users may want a workflow connect to BQ. So I prefer to keep it this way for future extension.
replies.author: trucleduc

replies.bodyText: I am a bit confused. The purpose of exporting is to load the FHIR resources into Dataflow for further processing, thus how the data is loaded (e.g. via GCS or BQ) is not important. If users would like to apply transformations before sending the data to BQ, they can still export via GCS, and then use BigQueryIO to write the data. Did I miss anything?
replies.author: lastomato

replies.bodyText:
I see your point. That makes sense for this implementation because we will read the resources back anyway. However, export FHIR resources to BigQuery allows users to specify different schema, which could be non-trivial for BigqueryIO to reproduce.
I made the change anyway and if there is a need like above, we can add the ExportBQ later.
replies.author: trucleduc

replies.bodyText: I think I am missing something :) Let's talk offline.
replies.author: lastomato

replies.bodyText: Talked offline, one use case Truc was thinking about is that users might want to use the ExportResources API to flatten the FHIR resources first, then load the flatten resources into the pipeline.
replies.author: lastomato

timeline.bodyText: Should we return errors with exporting in the Result?
timeline.author: lastomato

replies.bodyText: Export is extremely unlikely to have error with individual resources (and if there is it usually occurs for all resources). The error is usually at the LRO level, which the workflow will fail with IOException.
replies.author: trucleduc

replies.bodyText: In that case, you probably won't need to wrap it in a Result class, since you can return a PCollection directly.
replies.author: lastomato

timeline.author: lastomato

timeline.bodyText: Please cache this object, otherwise we will create a Gson object for each element.
timeline.author: lastomato

replies.bodyText: Gson class in also not serializable. So I reverted back to the original version. Do you know what is the good way to do it? For me, I think Gson object is not a big deal though as this transform is expected to operation at FHIR store level, which is usually a few.
replies.author: trucleduc

replies.bodyText: Have you tried to make it a static field? Static fields are implicitly transient.
replies.author: lastomato

replies.bodyText: Done. Thanks for tolerating a Java newbie :-)
replies.author: trucleduc

timeline.author: lastomato

replies.bodyText: No, DeidentifyConfig is NOT serializable and we don't want to change this auto-generated API.
replies.author: trucleduc
